s for serial stalkers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Nye",,"Baroness Nye","HL3965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654720","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>We have a long track record in this country of implementing tobacco control measures which are supported by a strong evidence base, and the new tobacco control plan will build on this approach. As part of our development of the tobacco control plan, stakeholders were invited to give views during the initial stages. This included representatives of the independent retail sector. We will continue to consult with our stakeholders before introducing any new tobacco control measures.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654720/answer",,,,,"HL3967","2016-12-20T15:23:59.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654720/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654720/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-08","Tobacco","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will publish a full evidence base, including any supporting research, for each measure contained in their forthcoming tobacco control strategy.","true","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL3966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654721","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>We have a long track record in this country of implementing tobacco control measures which are supported by a strong evidence base, and the new tobacco control plan will build on this approach. As part of our development of the tobacco control plan, stakeholders were invited to give views during the initial stages. This included representatives of the independent retail sector. We will continue to consult with our stakeholders before introducing any new tobacco control measures.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654721/answer",,,,,"HL3966","2016-12-20T15:23:59.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654721/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654721/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-08","Tobacco","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, and how, they will ensure that the views of the independent retail sector will be taken into account when putting together their forthcoming tobacco control strategy.","true","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL3967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654722","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-21","<p>Defra takes the issue of illegal trafficking of puppies very seriously. The action we have taken to tackle illegal puppy movements covers the key areas in the supply of trafficked puppies. Responsibility for stopping the illegal movement of puppies begins in the country where they are born. Where puppies have been discovered to have been moved into the UK using falsely certified pet passport paperwork my officials have raised the issue with authorities in the relevant countries. We also have effective border controls in place. These require all pet animals travelling into Great Britain on approved routes to have documentary and identity checks at the border. There are stringent penalties available against individual found to be breaking the rules by illegally moving dogs into the country.</p><p> </p><p>Defra and the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) have and continue to work constructively with other government agencies and animal welfare charities to share intelligence on illegal movements of puppies. APHA has provided Border Force officials with the requirements that dogs and puppies entering the UK must meet. APHA works closely with Border Force colleagues to assist them in reducing the illegal trafficking of puppies.</p><p> </p><p>Finally the illegal trafficking of puppies is ultimately driven by demand. Defra has published guidance for consumers on the responsible purchase of pet animals. It has worked closely with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group to drive up standards for online advertisements making potential pet owners and website operators more aware of rogue dealers and this work will continue.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654722/answer",,,,,"HL3969","2016-12-21T15:33:47.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654722/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654722/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-08","Dogs: Smuggling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what guidance they have given to Border Force regarding the illegal trafficking of puppies.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL3968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654723","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-21","<p>Defra takes the issue of illegal trafficking of puppies very seriously. The action we have taken to tackle illegal puppy movements covers the key areas in the supply of trafficked puppies. Responsibility for stopping the illegal movement of puppies begins in the country where they are born. Where puppies have been discovered to have been moved into the UK using falsely certified pet passport paperwork my officials have raised the issue with authorities in the relevant countries. We also have effective border controls in place. These require all pet animals travelling into Great Britain on approved routes to have documentary and identity checks at the border. There are stringent penalties available against individual found to be breaking the rules by illegally moving dogs into the country.</p><p> </p><p>Defra and the Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) have and continue to work constructively with other government agencies and animal welfare charities to share intelligence on illegal movements of puppies. APHA has provided Border Force officials with the requirements that dogs and puppies entering the UK must meet. APHA works closely with Border Force colleagues to assist them in reducing the illegal trafficking of puppies.</p><p> </p><p>Finally the illegal trafficking of puppies is ultimately driven by demand. Defra has published guidance for consumers on the responsible purchase of pet animals. It has worked closely with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group to drive up standards for online advertisements making potential pet owners and website operators more aware of rogue dealers and this work will continue.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654723/answer",,,,,"HL3968","2016-12-21T15:33:47.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654723/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654723/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-08","Dogs: Smuggling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to minimise the illegal trafficking of puppies.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL3969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654724","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Government proposes to modernise the laws on Animal Establishments Licensing Schemes including the laws that regulate dog breeding and selling. This proposal was supported by the majority of those that responded to our earlier public consultation.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654724/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T15:34:13.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654724/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654724/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-08","Breeding and Sale of Dogs (Welfare) Act 1999","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of the Breeding and Sale of Dogs (Welfare) Act 1999.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL3970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654725","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-21","<p>The number of defendants that have been proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and thereafter been found guilty and sentenced at all courts for running a breeding establishment for dogs without a licence from a local authority, in England and Wales, from 2011 to 2015, can be viewed in the table below. It is possible that others may have been prosecuted under the Pet Animals Act 1951 for selling dogs without a pet shop licence. Records held for convictions under the 1951 Act do not, however, show what species of animal were involved.</p><p> </p><p>Prosecutions under the Breeding of Dogs Act 1973</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Outcome</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Proceeded against</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Found guilty</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sentenced</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fined</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The figures given in the table relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences, it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p><p>Every effort has been made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. It is important to note, however, that this data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services – Ministry of Justice. Data extracted on 9 December 2016</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654725/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T16:06:29.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654725/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654725/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-12-08","Dogs: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many puppy dealers have been (1) prosecuted, or (2) fined for selling puppies without a licence.","false","Biography information for Baroness Redfern",,"Baroness Redfern","HL3971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654726","Department for Education","false","2016-12-16","<p>In the 2016 Budget, the Government announced that it would conduct a review into the gaps in support for lifetime learning, including for flexible and part-time study. The review is on-going and the Government will announce its next steps shortly. Additionally, the Government is also devolving the Adult Education Budget to Mayoral Combined Authorities and London, as local areas should be well placed to develop a responsive lower-level skills offer that meets the needs of individuals and the local labour market</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654726/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T14:49:47.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654726/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654726/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-08","Adult Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to develop an adult education strategy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Shephard of Northwold",,"Baroness Shephard of Northwold","HL3972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654727","Department for Education","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Government has made a series of changes to help ensure education policy better supports all ages. In the 2016 Budget, the Government announced that it would conduct a review into the gaps in support for lifetime learning, including for flexible and part-time study. The review is on-going and the Government will announce its next steps shortly.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654727/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-20T15:26:03.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654727/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654727/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-08","Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that education policy relates to learners of all ages and backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Baroness Shephard of Northwold",,"Baroness Shephard of Northwold","HL3973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654728","Home Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>All police forces in England and Wales are expected to publish their own record level Use of Force data (including in mental health settings). We expect a sub-set of the data collected to form part of the overall Home Office 2017-18 Annual Data Requirement, which will be published on an annual basis.</p><p>The Government has written to each Police and Crime Commissioner, Chief Constable and Chair of local Mental Health Crisis Care Concordat Partnerships to ask them to make arrangements for the joint identification and scrutiny of any use of Taser in a mental health setting in their areas. It is a matter for local partnerships to determine the most appropriate arrangements for doing so.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654728/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T11:57:10.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654728/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654728/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-08","Police: Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 November (HL Deb, col 1931), (1) which authority will be responsible for requesting details of local areas' use of any Taser in a mental health setting, and (2) what protocols will be used to determine how, and when, any such request is made.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL3974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654729","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>A list of local areas which will receive funding under the improving health-based places of safety capital scheme is attached.</p><p> </p><p>Applications for funding were assessed against criteria agreed jointly by the Department of Health, the Home Office and NHS England. To be considered for funding, bids had to demonstrate sustainability and how they would satisfy local need and demand, how they would reduce the use of police stations for adults detained under Section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983 and support the elimination of the use of police stations for children and young people under the age of 18, compliance with relevant legislation, and a commitment to shared learning. Applications also had to be developed and agreed by local Crisis Care Concordat Groups. Full details of the criteria for applications are attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654729/answer","Improving places of safety - approved_projects.pdf ; HL3975 Improving places of safety criteria for applications.docx","Improving places of safety - approved_projects.pdf ; HL3975 Improving places of safety criteria for applications.docx","PROJECT LIST  ; CRITERIA FOR APPLICATIONS","PROJECT LIST  ; CRITERIA FOR APPLICATIONS",,"2016-12-19T15:36:14.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654729/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654729/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-08","Mental Health Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 23 November (HL Deb, col 1932), what is the breakdown of the 88 projects in receipt of a share of £15 million of investment to increase safe places, and what are the criteria used to allocate funding.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL3975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654730","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>£1.7 billion of investment for Accelerated Construction was announced at the Autumn Statement. This will see up to 15,000 homes started on surplus public sector land this Parliament.</p><p>We are currently undertaking detailed project scoping. Further details about the programme will be made available on completion of this work.</p><p>Furthermore, the recently launched £3 billion Home Building Fund, running to 2020-21 provides development and infrastructure loan finance, with £1 billion of this targeted at small and custom builders which the Department intends to deliver 25,500 new homes by 2020.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654730/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T13:36:20.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654730/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654730/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Young of Cookham on 23 November (HL Deb, col 1937), (1) what assessment they have made, and will make, of successfully bringing small builders back into the housing market, (2) how many small building companies have been involved in the project, and (3) where the small building firms are located.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL3976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654731","Department for Education","false","2016-12-15","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw. I have asked him to write to you and a copy of his reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654731/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T15:13:31.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654731/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654731/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-08","Pupils: Bullying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Nash on 24 November (HL Deb, col 2046), (1) how Ofsted inspectors categorise incidents of bullying, discriminatory and prejudicial behaviour, either direct or indirect, including racist, sexist, disability and homophobic bullying, use of derogatory language, and racist incidents, in relation to the wider assessment of the school; (2) what specific measures and actions Ofsted recommends after such incidents are recorded; and (3) how progress is monitored and recorded.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL3977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654732","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>I refer my noble friend to the Written Statement laid (attached) on the 21 November. The statement can be viewed on line at: http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Lords/2016-11-21/HLWS274/</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654732/answer","WMS - Social Housing.pdf","WMS - Social Housing.pdf","Social Housing WMS - HLWS274","Social Housing WMS - HLWS274",,"2016-12-21T17:24:25.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654732/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654732/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Social Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 24 November (HL Deb, col 2050), what is the new information regarding pay to stay that led to a change of policy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL3978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654733","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>The review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures began with a 6 week call for evidence on 24 October, closing on 4 December. The call for evidence generated a lot of interest from the general public, as well as from a variety of interest groups, local authorities, trade bodies and industry. We are now looking in depth at the evidence and aim to publish our findings and any proposals in spring 2017.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654733/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T17:22:04.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654733/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654733/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to complete and then publish the review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Hindhead",,"Lord Smith of Hindhead","HL3979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654734","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-19","<p>The current European Infrastructure Technical Standard for Interoperability (TSI) allows platform heights of 550mm or 760mm above rail level (ARL). In addition, the UK currently has a ‘National Technical Rule’ which includes a ‘Specific Case’ allowing platform heights of 915mm ARL, reflecting the historic platform height on the majority of our existing network.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 is not, as such, proposing to specify a train floor height. What we will be asking rolling stock manufacturers (RSMs) to do is to provide level access to a platform height of 1115mm, or, if they do not believe that is achievable, to tell us at what height platform they could provide level access.</p><p> </p><p>We have proposed to the European Commission an amendment to the current European standards to allow for our preferred platform height and we remain in discussions with them with a view to securing the ability to adopt our preferred platform height through these or alternative means.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654734/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T14:10:35.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654734/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654734/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, under the current technical specifications for interoperability, what height differences between station platforms and top of rail level are allowed for new HS2 stations; what heights are specified by HS2 for new train floor height and station platform heights; and what derogation, if any, they have sought and received to those heights for new HS2 platforms.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL3980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654735","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-22","<p>The Government is committed to returning housing associations to the private sector where they clearly belong. We made changes to the Housing and Planning Act 2016 to address controls identified by the Office for National Statistics. Following on from this we will be laying regulations under section 93 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 in the New Year.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654735/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T15:36:59.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654735/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654735/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Housing Associations: Private Sector","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 30 November (HL3538), what action they are taking to enable the Office for National Statistics to reclassify housing associations to the private sector.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654736","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>The eight working groups that have been established since the passing of the Housing &amp; Planning Act 2016 are made up of a wide range of stakeholders including industries, Local Government and third sector organisations. The working groups are:</p><ul><li>Starter Homes Working Groups</li><li>Housing Tenure Information Working Group</li><li>Private Rented Sector Electrical Safety Working Group</li><li>Client Money Protection Working Group</li><li>Secure Tenancies Working Group</li><li>The IT Consultative working Group</li><li>DCLG Fraud Working Group</li><li>Income Based Rents for Social Tenants Working Group (no longer in operation)</li></ul>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654736/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T17:25:07.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654736/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654736/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Housing and Planning Act 2016","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 29 November (HL 3353), what is the composition of the eight working groups that have been established since the passing of the Housing and Planning Act 2016.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654737","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>We have had responses from over 600 organisations to the public consultation since the Housing and Planning Act 2016 came into force, including a range of housing groups, councils, and charities.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654737/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-21T17:32:11.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654737/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654737/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Housing and Planning Act 2016","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 29 November (HL3354), which organisations have responded to the public consultation since the Housing and Planning Act 2016 came into force.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654738","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the Statement (attached) I gave on 5 December, repeating the answer given earlier that day by my rt Hon Friend, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, to an Urgent Question on Dame Louise Casey’s review into opportunity and integration.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654738/answer","HL3984 Casey Review.pdf","HL3984 Casey Review.pdf","Casey Review","Casey Review",,"2016-12-19T15:28:21.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654738/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654738/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Opportunity and Integration Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to give a formal response to the Casey Review.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654739","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-22","<p>The Government continues to demonstrate its support for the community led housing sector and we encourage community led groups, including housing co-operatives, to apply for funding from the expanded and more flexible Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme. Operational delivery of the programme is delegated to the Homes and Communities Agency and the Greater London Authority and so they will work with individual providers. However, my officials also regularly meet representatives of the community led housing sector, including the Confederation of Co-operative Housing (CCH), to discuss how they can positively contribute to the delivery of new housing.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654739/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-22T11:55:57.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654739/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654739/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Housing: Cooperatives","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they last met a co-operative housing provider to discuss the provision of more co-operative housing.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654740","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>The independent review group of the Cabinet and Pole Siting Code of Practice was chaired by a representative of the Office of the Telecommunications Adjudicator and its membership comprised of representatives from the following organisations:</p><p> </p><p>Openreach</p><p> </p><p>Virgin Media</p><p> </p><p>Sky</p><p> </p><p>UK Competitive Telecommunications Association (UKCTA)</p><p> </p><p>Planning Officers Society</p><p> </p><p>National Parks Authority</p><p> </p><p>The National Association for Areas of Outstanding Natural Beauty</p><p> </p><p>Historic England</p><p> </p><p>The group can be contacted through its secretariat which is provided by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport. Representatives from other Government departments also attended meetings as required.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654740/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T16:16:31.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654740/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654740/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Telecommunications: Planning Permission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 29 November and 6 December (HL3375 and HL3759), who are the members of the independent group representing communications and planning interests which monitors non-compliance with the code of practice, and how the group can be contacted.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL3986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654780","Attorney General","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Government Car Service stopped providing individual cars in April 2012. Therefore, there is no individual journey data available from 1 April 2012. The Department for Transport, as part of their transparency agenda, publishes information on the costs incurred by each government department through the use of vehicles provided by the Government Car Services.</p><p> </p><p>Information on recent years can be found via the Gov.UK website below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/ministerial-cars" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/ministerial-cars</a></p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654780/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T12:58:57.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654780/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654780/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-12-08","Attorney General: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, with reference to the charges for Government Car Services supplied ministerial cars between 2012 and 2015, published on 17 December 2017, what the (a) purpose, (b) distance travelled and (c) cost was of each journey booked by his Office.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","56816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654781","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-13","<p>The transition period for full implementation of the Union Customs Code runs to the end of 2019. HM Revenue and Customs is carrying out this work without the need for additional resources as part of its business as usual activities.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654781/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:36:03.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654781/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654781/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Customs: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many additional staff have been allocated to assist with the implementation of the new EU Customs Code which was introduced on 1 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","56725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654782","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-13","<p>In line with the International Development (Official Development Assistance Target) Act 2015, HM Treasury allocates sufficient Official Development Assistance (ODA) funding to maintain an ODA: Gross National Income (GNI) ratio of 0.7% - the only country in the G7 and G20 to meet the UN commitment. This commitment takes account of wider public spending considerations.</p><p> </p><p>The amount spent on ODA will continue to rise in each calendar year, reflecting the Office for Budget Responsibility’s latest economic growth forecasts.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654782/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:53:22.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654782/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654782/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it is his policy that 0.7 per cent of gross national income is the maximum amount to be allocated to overseas development assistance.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","56726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654783","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Union Customs Code (UCC) provides for a transition arrangement for re-authorising the customs facilitations for traders through to 2019. To date HM Revenue and Customs has processed 291 UCC Authorised Economic Operator applications which is the major trade facilitation measure within the UCC.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654783/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:28:18.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654783/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654783/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Customs: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many applications made pursuant to the implementation of the new EU Customs Code have been processed.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","56733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654784","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-16","<p>As noted in the 2012 report by the Migration Advisory Committee (MAC), the empirical literature suggests that the impact of migration on aggregate productivity may be mixed and heavily dependent on the type of migrant coming to the UK. Migrants may increase productivity either through a simple ‘batting average’ effect if they work in higher productivity roles relative to the average for non-migrants, or through increasing the productivity of UK workers through greater specialisation and knowledge transfer. In this report, the MAC established the key role played by skilled migrants in raising productivity. Further, the 2014 MAC report, ‘Migrants in low-skilled work’, found low skilled migrants have a neutral impact on UK-born employment rates, GDP per head and productivity.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654784/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T09:09:09.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654784/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654784/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an assessment of the effect on (a) per capita GDP and (b) overall productivity of changes in the migrant share of the adult population.","false","Biography information for John Penrose","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","56709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654785","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-16","<p>Since 2002, 1,172 sports clubs have been deregistered as community amateur sports clubs.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654785/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T11:53:21.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654785/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654785/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Sports: Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many amateur sports clubs have lost their community amateur sports club status since 2002.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","56712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654786","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-13","<p>It is not possible at this stage to give a reliable estimate of the costs to the Exchequer of the eventual outcome of the Franked Investment Income Group Litigation Order. This litigation is ongoing and raises several fundamental legal issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Trust Accounts of HM Revenue and Customs published annually reflect provisions and contingent amounts in relation to this and other items of important on-going litigation. This is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmrc-annual-report-and-accounts-2015-to-2016.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654786/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:32:55.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654786/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654786/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what costs (a) have and (b) will accrue to the public purse as a result of the 2012 Franked Investment income judgment.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","56757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654787","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-16","<p>Two judgments in the Franked Investment Income Group Litigation Order case were handed down in 2012, by the UK Supreme Court on 23 May and by the Court of Justice of the European Union on 13 November. Since those decisions, HM Revenue and Customs has made payments of £1,490,455,098 less tax withheld under the restitution interest provisions introduced by Finance (No.2) Act 2015 of £324,402,752, a net sum of £1,166,052,346.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654787/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T11:56:10.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654787/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654787/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Taxation: Rebates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much the Government has had to pay in tax rebates since the 2012 Franked Investment Income judgment.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","56743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654788","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-15","<p>1. A full list of all Armed Forces and Emergency Services charities and other related good causes supported with funding committed at the Autumn Statement has been published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/libor-funding-applications/use-of-banking-fines" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/libor-funding-applications/use-of-banking-fines</a>.</p><p> </p><p>2. The breakdown as per the categories requested is as follows:</p><ol><li><p>Facilities based at Ministry of Defence sites – £3,465,824.</p></li><li><p>Charities and organisations affiliated to the Ministry of Defence – £12,304,946.</p></li><li><p>Official Ministry of Defence-run charities and events – £2,932,000.</p></li></ol>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654788/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T15:01:32.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654788/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654788/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Charities: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Autumn Statement 2016, paragraph 5.14, how much of the £102 million support for armed forces and emergency services charities and other related good causes has been allocated to (a) facilities based at Ministry of Defence sites, (b) charities and organisations affiliated to the Ministry of Defence and (c) official Ministry of Defence-run charities and events.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","56783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654789","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-13","<p>The government does not intend to provide commentary on specific commercial decisions in the North Sea.</p><p> </p><p>The government is committed to making the most of the UK’s oil and gas resources. In support of this, the government has announced substantial fiscal reform in the last few years, including significant tax cuts. This will ensure oil and gas companies are well-placed to invest in this vital industry, extend the life of existing assets and safeguard jobs.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654789/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:54:48.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654789/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654789/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Shell: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential effect of Shell's sale of its North Sea field assets on the sustainability of UK jobs in that area.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","56830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654790","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-15","<p>The government is considering the future of the Levy Control Framework and will set this out at the Spring Budget 2017.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654790/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T15:00:13.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654790/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654790/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-08","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 3.22 in the Autumn Statement 2016, whether he will make an announcement on the future of the Levy Control Framework in (a) the Spring Budget 2017 or (b) the Autumn Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","56845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654791","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Department will publish a summary of the responses to the consultation on the &quot;Improving the Efficiency of Council Tax Collection&quot;, together with its own response, as soon as possible.</p><p><br></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654791/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:11:34.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654791/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654791/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to publish the outcomes of his Department's consultation on Council Tax collection which closed in November 2015.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","56835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654792","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-13","<p>Since the launch of the Help to Buy: Equity Loan, Help to Buy: Mortgage Guarantee and Help to Buy: NewBuy schemes, the total number of homes sold under all three schemes total 183,795 in the UK, of which 10,023 are in Greater London, 317 in the London borough of Newham, and 132 in East Ham constituency.</p><p>Information on age of purchaser is not included in the statistics.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654792/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:55:50.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654792/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654792/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Help to Buy Scheme: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many young people have received assistance from the Government's Help to Buy scheme in (a) the UK, (b) Greater London, (c) the London Borough of Newham and (d) East Ham constituency.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","56836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654793","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-13","<p>98% of the 832 Chagossians that responded to the public consultation indicated that they were in favour of resettlement.</p><p>After being asked to take into consideration the level of health, education and facilities that could be reasonably provided, 25% of the 832 Chagossians were in favour of resettlement.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654793/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T17:56:31.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654793/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654793/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-08","Chagos Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the oral contribution of the Minister of State for Europe and the Americas of 17 November 2016, Official Report, column 387, what proportion of the 837 Chagossian people surveyed indicated that they wished to reside on the  Chagos islands before they were asked to take into consideration what life would be like on those islands.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","56763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654794","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-16","<p>Ministers and officials from both departments meet when necessary to discuss a range of issues of interest to both departments.</p><p>Older people have a wide range of different housing needs, ranging from suitable and appropriately located market housing through to residential institutions and we are clear in the National Planning Policy Framework that councils should plan for a mix of housing, based on the needs of different groups in the community, including older people. We strengthened planning guidance last year to reinforce our expectations.</p><p>Housing is an important element to people's health and wellbeing and provision of suitable housing can and does play a role within the wider integration of health and social care to which we are committed.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654794/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T13:35:42.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654794/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654794/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-08","Housing: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health on the health benefits of retirement housing and its potential in reducing local authority adult social care bills.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","56754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654795","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport has had one meeting with the Information Commissioner since her appointment. The Information Commissioner has also met with other DCMS Ministers to discuss a range of relevant policy issues.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654795/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T13:23:38.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654795/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654795/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Information Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many meetings she has held with the UK Information Commissioner since her appointment.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","56720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654796","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-16","<p>I raised the issue of South Korea's dog meat trade with the South Korean Ambassador on 12 September. As I said during the Westminster Hall debate on the dog meat trade in South Korea on 12 September, high-profile global events such as the Olympic Games can be a catalyst for positive change. The South Korean government will be aware that the high profile of the Winter Games could cast a spotlight on issues such as the dog meat trade.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654796/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T12:05:13.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654796/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654796/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-08","South Korea: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made recent representations to the South Korean government on implications of the South Korean dog meat trade for countries due to participate in the next Winter Olympics.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","56711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654797","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>The government strategy for sport and physical activity ‘Sporting Future: A New Strategy for An Active Nation’ highlights the importance of diversity in senior leadership. On 31 October this year Sport England and UK Sport published a new Code for Sports Governance, fulfilling an action set out in Sporting Future. The code requires each funded organisation to adopt a target of a minimum of 30% of each gender on its board, demonstrate a strong commitment to achieving greater diversity on its board, identify actions to support diversity targets and publish information on fostering diversity including annual updates on progress. The governance code will be mandatory for all sports bodies seeking public funding in the next funding period.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England and UK Sport are also working with funded National Governing Bodies and partners to ensure good practice is adhered to when constructing job descriptions and writing adverts, and are working with expert organisations such as Sporting Equals and Women in Sport to ensure a more diverse range of people are aware of vacancies within the sector as they arise.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654797/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T16:44:25.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654797/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654797/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Sports: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 2 December 2016 to Question 55347, on sports: equality, if she will promote the application of similar measures more generally throughout sport to address diversity at the top.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","56803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654798","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>DCMS is fully committed to ensuring diversity in all public appointments. In the first two quarters of 2016/17, 50% of new DCMS appointments went to women and 18% to BAME candidates.</p><p> </p><p>The DCMS public appointments team are always working to find ways to attract a wider pool of talent and to meet - and exceed - diversity targets. The team works closely with the Cabinet Office to identify potential barriers and has put in place a number of actions to overcome them - including bespoke advertising plans for each appointment campaign, targeting under-represented groups, and outreach events such as one aimed at women being equally represented on public sector boards.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654798/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T11:29:29.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654798/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654798/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to support and promote the recommendations of the Parker Review on increasing the ethnic diversity of UK boards in appointments for which her Department is responsible.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","56865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654799","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>Non-executive members of the Channel 4 Corporation board are appointed by Ofcom with the approval of the Secretary of State. Ofcom advertised for four vacancies for candidates with specific sector skills and experience. The Secretary of State approved the four candidates on the basis that they met the skills and experience set out the advertised job descriptions.</p><p> </p><p>The OCPA (Office for the Commissioner for Public Appointments) code, which is a measure of good practice in public appointments, is very clear that it is approprate for Ministers to suggest potential candidates to be invited to apply for public appointments.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654799/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T13:17:42.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654799/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654799/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department proposed candidates to Ofcom for vacant Channel 4 non-executive director posts in 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","56858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654800","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>Non-executive members of the Channel 4 Corporation board are appointed by Ofcom with the approval of the Secretary of State. Ofcom advertised for four vacancies for candidates with specific sector skills and experience. The Secretary of State approved the four candidates on the basis that they met the skills and experience set out the advertised job descriptions.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654800/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T13:19:31.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654800/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654800/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, for what reason she rejected the appointment of Althea Efunshile as a non-executive director of Channel 4.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","56859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654801","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>DCMS is committed to ensuring diversity in all public appointments. In the first two quarters of 2016/17, 50% of new DCMS appointments went to women and 18% to BAME candidates</p><p> </p><p>Regarding the recent Channel 4 board posts, the Secretary of State approved the four candidates on the basis that they met the skills and experience set out the advertised job descriptions.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654801/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T13:20:32.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654801/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654801/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what account she took of the diversity of public appointments in her decision relating to the approval of Ofcom's candidates for vacant Channel 4  non-executive director posts.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","56860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654802","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Secretary of State can ask a Minister to meet with candidates deemed appointable at interview before making a final decision, or indeed meet them herself. There were no meetings or conversations between ministers and any candidates in relation to the Channel 4 board appointments.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654802/answer",,,,,"56862","2016-12-13T13:21:43.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654802/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654802/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many candidates for vacant Channel 4 non-executive director posts her Department has discussed the appointment process for those roles with on what dates in 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","56861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654803","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Secretary of State can ask a Minister to meet with candidates deemed appointable at interview before making a final decision, or indeed meet them herself. There were no meetings or conversations between ministers and any candidates in relation to the Channel 4 board appointments.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654803/answer",,,,,"56861","2016-12-13T13:21:43.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654803/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654803/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","Channel Four Television: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many candidates for vacant Channel 4 non-executive director posts were interviewed by Ministers of her Department on what dates in 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","56862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654804","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-13","<p>Cyber security is a core part of the Computing Science GCSE curriculum, ensuring students are taught about cyber resilience in secondary school. Work is also underway to ensure cyber security is taught more widely in schools to equip children with the required skills to stay safe online.</p><p> </p><p>Further, under the government’s National Cyber Security Programme, DCMS and DfE are working closely to develop an extracurricular national programme to help develop cyber security skills among talented children aged 14-18 from across the social spectrum, and help them pursue a career in cyber security.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654804/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T13:24:58.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654804/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654804/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-08","ICT: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Education on including the subject of cyber resilience in the teaching of ICT in schools.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","56828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654805","Department for Education","false","2016-12-13","<p>We want to make it as simple as possible for schools and local authorities to determine eligibility for free school meals (FSM).</p><p>We understand that some local authorities have found this approach can be an effective tactic. However, it does not provide a complete or sustainable solution to automatic registration for FSM. We do not consider further legislation to be necessary for this particular approach.</p><p>To support FSM registration, the department provides an online eligibility checking facility; and a model registration form for schools to use within their enrolment process.</p><p>The department is exploring what opportunities exist in the longer term to make FSM registration processes more efficient.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654805/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T15:58:51.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654805/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654805/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-08","Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that housing benefit data is used by local authorities in England to identify and automatically register all children eligible for free school meals.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","56826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654806","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-13","<p>Over the last two years, the Department has sent eight letters to veterans asking them to supply any information in respect of historic investigations by the Police Service of Northern Ireland.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654806/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T17:17:21.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654806/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654806/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-08","Historical Enquiries Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many letters his Department has sent in the last two years asking soldiers to come forward with any information that could help the Police Service of Northern Ireland in its historical investigations.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","56837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654807","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-13","<p>There are 27 submarines due to be dismantled as part of the Submarine Dismantling Programme. The oldest submarine was retired from service in 1980. 19 have been decommissioned and a further eight submarines that are still in service will also be in scope.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654807/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T18:03:28.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654807/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654807/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-08","Submarines: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Royal Navy submarines are due to be scrapped; and for how long those submarines have been decommissioned.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","56838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654808","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave her on 6 June 2016 to Question 38553. The Army does not define roles as frontline or non-frontline. All soldiers, regardless of capbadge, are trained for a wide range of operational tasks and environments, including combat. Established procedures are in place to ensure that Service personnel under the age of 18 are not deployed on operations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654808/answer","20160606_38553_Armed_Forces_Young_People.docx","20160606_38553_Armed_Forces_Young_People.docx","38553 - WQnA extract on Armed Forces: Young People","38553 - WQnA extract on Armed Forces: Young People",,"2016-12-14T16:12:56.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654808/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654808/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-08","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether it remains the Government's policy to restrict army applicants aged under 16 years and six months from enlisting for frontline combat and driving roles.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","56737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654809","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave him on 12 December 2016 to Questions 56546, 56547 and 56548.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654809/answer","20161212_56546_War_Widows_Compensation.docx","20161212_56546_War_Widows_Compensation.docx","56546 - WQnA extract on War Widows Compensation","56546 - WQnA extract on War Widows Compensation",,"2016-12-13T16:17:14.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654809/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654809/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-08","War Widows: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent meetings he has held as part of his Department's review into the Government's policy on compensation for war widows who re-married between 1973 and 2005.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","56722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654811","Department for Education","false","2016-12-19","<p>The first apprentice panel will be in place before the Institute for Apprenticeships goes live in April 2017. We are considering options for recruitment and will put in place a process to ensure that membership is diverse and drawn from different occupations, backgrounds and areas of the country.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654811/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-19T17:31:13.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654811/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654811/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-08","Apprenticeship Delivery Board","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the process is for appointing the advisory panel of apprentices for the Institute for Apprenticeships and Technical Education; and how she plans to ensure that that panel's membership is drawn from different occupations, backgrounds and areas of the country.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","56724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654812","Department for Education","false","2016-12-13","<p>The Skills Funding Agency, which became a Department for Education agency following the announcements in July of changes to Ministerial responsibilities, has an existing strategy to shrink its estate. Since 2010, the Skills Funding Agency has reduced its accommodation footprint and it has announced the closure of three further offices - Birmingham, Reading and Plymouth - by 31 March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We have no other plans to close any offices in the Department for Education estate or those of our agencies. We will continue to keep our estate under review to ensure our business is operating efficiently and effectively.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654812/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-13T16:26:52.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654812/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654812/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-08","Department for Education: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans any office closures for her Department or its departmental agencies.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","56731"
