"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654466","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-16","<p>The operation of the legal aid scheme is continually monitored by both the Ministry of Justice and the Legal Aid Agency, with legal aid statistics published on a quarterly basis. In addition to this, we are committed to reviewing Parts 1 and 2 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 by April 2018. The timing of this review will be announced in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654466/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T12:57:32.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654466/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654466/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Administration of Justice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the effect of the Legal Aid Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 on access to justice for the most vulnerable people in society.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","56494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654467","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654467/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-12T17:33:00.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654467/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654467/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Universal Credit: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on how many occasions appeal cases for hearing at tribunals have been adjourned as a result of the Department for Work and Pensions not providing sufficient information on universal credit in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","56468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654468","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-20","<p>We are exploring further the opportunities for problem solving approaches following completion of the joint judicial working group report earlier this year. A number of courts are already using problem solving approaches, including clustered listing of drug review hearings, female-specific courts in Manchester and Aberdeen, and the Choices and Consequences programme in St Albans. I have visited a number of courts where problem solving approaches have been developed at a grassroots level in local communities, and will set out further plans in due course.</p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654468/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-20T16:49:15.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654468/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654468/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the problem-solving courts pilot programme announced by her Department in May 2016 will begin.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","56475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654469","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 15 December 2016 to Question 41046 <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-20/41046/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-20/41046/</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654469/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-18T12:35:46.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654469/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654469/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","National Offender Management Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much (a) the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) and (b) her Department spent on external consultancy fees relating to NOMS in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","56476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654470","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>This information is available on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654470/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-12T17:40:04.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654470/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654470/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Prisons: Vandalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted of the offence of throwing any article or substance into a prison without authorisation since that offence came into force; and how many such people have received the maximum sentence for that offence.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","56477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654471","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-16","<p>We want prisons to be places of hard work and high ambition, with incentives for prisoners to learn. We also want prison staff to prioritise education and employment opportunities. We are giving governors greater control over their budgets to bring in education and employment schemes that deliver real results. More private sector companies now employ ex-offenders than ever before, but we are keen to increase the number of employers who can provide valuable vocational work for offenders in prison, and who are able to offer them employment on release.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654471/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T13:01:06.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654471/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654471/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Offenders: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to incentivise employers to recruit ex-offenders.","true","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","56433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654472","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-15","<p>HMCTS does not hold this information centrally for First-tier Tribunals and this information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654472/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-15T17:20:16.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654472/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654472/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of First-tier Tribunal users represented themselves as litigants in person; and what proportion of those tribunals found in favour of the appellant for each (a) chamber and jurisdiction as defined by the Courts and Tribunals Judiciary in September 2016 and (b) quarter in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","56444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654473","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-25","<p>On Monday 5 December we launched a consultation on offences and penalties relating to causing death and serious injury.</p><p> </p><p>How police enforce the law is the responsibility of individual Chief Police Officers, taking into account the specific local problems and demands with which they are faced. When an apparent offence is reported or they observe an apparent offence, they will decide on the appropriate course of action.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654473/answer",,,,,,"2017-01-25T13:11:06.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654473/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654473/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Dangerous Driving: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Government's press release, entitled Killer drivers to face life sentences, published on 4 December 2016, if she will take further steps to improve the enforcement of offences related to dangerous driving.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","56460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654474","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-16","Full information on staffing in prisons in England and Wales is published in the NOMS Quarterly Workforce Bulletin available on the gov.uk website.","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654474/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T12:31:26.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654474/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654474/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison officers are employed in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Gordon Henderson","Sittingbourne and Sheppey","Gordon Henderson","56466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654475","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>We are committed to ensuring that victims get the support they need to cope with and, where possible, recover from crime. We have protected the overall level of funding for victims for five years and have allocated funding of nearly £100m in 2016/17 to fund crucial support services. For 2017/18 we have protected funding of over £6.4 million to 86 female rape support centres across England and Wales.</p><p>The Survivors Trust is one of two umbrella organisations representing the rape and sexual violence sector, the other being Rape Crisis England &amp; Wales. Organisations receiving funding from my department are members of one or both organisations.</p><p>Funding provided directly to The Survivors Trust 2011-16 principally relates to work to support the setting up of new female rape support centres. In 2016-17 no funding was provided to The Survivors Trust as the set up period for the new centres has been completed. All funding goes directly to rape support centres.</p><p>The table below shows the funding provided by my department to The Survivors Trust from 2009-10 to date:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£237,393</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£162,550.45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£339,340</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£362</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£101,859</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£149,629</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>I will ask my officials to review information held in relation to this allocation with the view to publication where it is appropriate to do so, and I will write to you further on this point in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654475/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-12T17:39:43.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654475/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654475/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Survivors Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much funding her Department provided to the Survivors Trust in each year since 2009-10; and if she will publish all files related to that funding allocation held by her Department.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","56450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654476","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>We are committed to ensuring that victims get the support they need to cope with and, where possible, recover from crime. We have protected the overall level of funding for victims for five years and have allocated funding of nearly £100m in 2016/17 to fund crucial support services. For 2017/18 we have protected funding of over £6.4 million to 86 female rape support centres across England and Wales.</p><p>The table below shows the funding provided by my department to Survivors Hull &amp; East Riding from 2009-10 to date:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£30,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£30,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£30,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£67,500 *</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£45,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£63,000 **</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>* includes 15 months funding of £22,500 to support child sexual abuse victims between January 2015 and March 2016 inclusive.</em></p><p><em>** includes 12 months funding of £18,000 to support child sexual abuse victims between April 2016 and March 2017 inclusive.</em></p><p>I will ask my officials to review information held in relation to this allocation with the view to publication where it is appropriate to do so, and I will write to you further on this point in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654476/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-12T17:33:15.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654476/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654476/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Survivors (Hull and East Riding)","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much funding her Department provided to Survivors (Hull and East Riding) in each year since 2009-10; and if she will publish all files related to that funding allocation held by her Department.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","56451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654477","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-16","<p>MoJ collects data on pay, broken down by gender, and plans to publish information in line with legislation.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654477/answer",,,,,,"2016-12-16T15:03:30.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654477/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654477/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-07","Ministry of Justice: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans her Department has to publish information on the gender pay gap among its employees.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","56608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654478","Ministry of Justice","true","2016-12-16","<p>The Government is clear that stalking and harassment, which cause misery for victims, are totally unacceptable. The fixated nature of stalking may result in a prolonged campaign sometimes lasting many years. So we are determined to do everything possible to protect all victims of stalking and stop perpetrators at the earliest opportunity – even before the stage at which a perpetrator might be prosecuted. That is why, following a public consultation, we have recently announced that there will be a new civil stalking protection order, to support victims of stalking at an earlier stage and address the perpetrator’s behaviours before they become entrenched.</p><p>The number of restraining orders imposed as result of stalking and harassment in England and Wales, 2014 and 2015 can be viewed in the table. Information on the specific restrictions included in a restraining order is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Nor do we hold data on how frequently perpetrators of these crimes seek to contact their victims through action in the civil or family courts. The courts do have powers to deal with unmeritorious claims and applications. The court may strike out the action as an abuse of process or issue an order restricting the litigant’s ability to continue with further applications or claims, either of its own motion or on request by a party to the proceedings.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654478/answer","Final table 56513-56515.xls","Final table 56513-56515.xls","Table 56513-56515","Table 56513-56515",,"2016-12-16T12:51:16.617Z","2017-01-19T17:42:13.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654478/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654478/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/654478/answer/previousversion/